		<section id="what-is-line">
			<div class="container">
				<h2>What is it?</h2>
				<p >Project Line is a queueing and point of sale algorithm designed to reduce on-premise wait time to zero minutes, service a customer as soon as they arrive, and maximize a business's throughput without adjusting staff or supply.</p>
				<p id="line-def-intro">Many of us look at waiting in lines as a supply problem. It is. Not enough seats at a restaurant? Too many guests at a theme park? A piece of this supply problem can be solved using information. By communicating between the business and the customer before the customer arrives, both groups benefit from more convenient lines and faster service.</p>
				<div class="row regular">
					<div class="six columns">
						<h3>For Customers</h3>
						<p>Less waiting, faster service.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="six columns">
						<h3>For Businesses</h3>
						<p>Increased efficiency, happy customers.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
		<section id="how-line">
			<div class="special container">
				<h2>How does it work?</h2>
				<p>The algorithm facilitates the communication between the customer and business to find the most convenient time for both parties. Once a time has been established, the algorithm will schedule the necessary resources to meet the order and time requirements.</p>
				<h2>How is this different?</h2>
				<p>Project Line lowers waiting times, optimizes orders with business resources, and improves customer convenience.</p>
				<p>Let's compare three types of lines: <br>the Line algorithm, basic virtual lines, and physical lines.</p>
				<ul>
					<li>A line of customers</li>
					<li>Waiting location flexibility</li>
					<li>Business to guest communication</li>
					<li>Online payment</li>
					<li>Guaranteed wait maximum</li>
					<li>Selective appointment</li>
					<li>Real-time GPS and traffic info</li>
					<li>Immediate on-premise service</li>
					<li>Optimize supply to meet demand</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>
